PfEIR vs. PfPR Sample Noise

House Effects, Trap Method, Age Corrections,

David Smith

2023-01-12

Overview

-

In this paper, we review and re-examine the data describing the PfEIR and the PfPR.

The point of this is to document and quantify several sources of sampling error, including potential sources of bias: house effects; heterogeneity in the PfPR introduced by the ages of the study population; and differences attributed to the methods used to catch/trap mosquitoes. The study is a review of at five studies that have previously examined the relationship or used the data for some other purpose [15].

History

  • In 1999, Beier et al. published a study that collected data describing estimates of the PfEIR and the PfPR collected at the same time and place [1]. Their analysis showed that the relationship was approximately log-linear.

  • In 2005, Hay et al. expanded the data, and redid the analysis with a slightly different emphasis [2].

  • Later that same year, Smith et al. fitted several mechanistic models to the data [3].

  • In 2011, Gething et al. published global maps of the PfPR, the PfEIR, and the Pf\(R_C\). The analysis updated the PfEIR - PfPR databases and revisited the relationship [4]

    • The updated data, including new PfPR-PfEIR pairs, was reported in the \(6^{th}\) supplement. The new data set included information about age of the study populations.

    • The PfEIR-PfPR analysis was revisited in the \(7^{th}\) supplement.

  • In 2015, Penny et al. re-examined the relationship between the PfEIR and the PfPR and identified systematic differences in the relationship based on the method of sampling mosquitoes. The inverted relationship used the PfPR to estimate the distribution of PfEIR at a national level [5]. Figure 2 replots the data.

House Effects

-

If the functional form is, indeed, an upper bound then we must be concerned about points that are above the curve. In a previous analysis (see Fig. 2a in Penny, et al., 2015), we identified systematic differences in the relationship based on the method of sampling mosquitoes. Given concerns about sampling bias, we tried to tried to identify which studies they came from. We found the following:

  • One set came from Thomson (red points and the red fitted line).

  • Two sets of studies came from around Killifi. One is a thesis by Kabiru, and the other a study by Mbogo (orange).

  • One set came from Bodker (purple).

  • The final set plotted below includes all the other studies not included in one of those sets (black):

Kilifi House Effect

The house effect of Kabiru / Mbogo is a factor of \(11\) at the lowest intensity, but declining by a factor of 3.2 for every factor of \(10\) increase in the EIR.

Thomson House Effect

The study by Thomson reports that they divided their estimates by a factor of 4.4, so we shift it back. Below, we have plotted the EIR estimates that were higher by a factor of 4.4 to reflect what was measured.

Bodker House Effect

The EIR estimates in the study by Bodker seems to be a factor of at least 10 higher than the rest.

EIR \(\rightarrow\) PR

While the EIR is measured infrequently, the PR is routinely measured in cross-sectional surveys. We can use the PR to estimate the EIR based on an empirical relationship between the EIR and the PR. Here, we start by re-examining an old database describing the EIR and the PR.

As a prelude, we start with a study sought to model the relationship between the EIR and the PR using mechanistic models (Smith, et al., 2005):

\[ x = 1 - \left( 1 + \frac{b E k}{r}\right)^{-1/k}\]

In many ways, we consider this functional form to be a sort of upper bound since it includes super-infection but ignores drug treatment. The parameter \(k\) builds in some flexibility. As \(k\) becomes very large, heterogeneity plays a larger role. As \(k\) becomes very small, the model is equivalent to Ross-Macdonald dynamics. In some sense, we take this as a strong prior on the data. One way it would not be an upper bound is if there were a substantial amount of exposure from outside the area, an idea we will explore later.

Here are the data (black points), the log-linear fits, and the function, with different values of \(k\). The higher the green curve, the smaller \(k\).

We were concerned about bias in the EIR estimates. In particular, we were suspicious of the points around aEIR of 1 that were above our green curves. We noted that these points came from four studies, and we further examined these studies to quantify a house effect. On the bases of those house effects (see below), we made some corrections.
